**Idea:**

We extract the digits of XXX using mod and division operations. Because the process of extracting digits from XXX (using X%10X \% 10X%10) naturally gives us the digits in reverse order of the original number, we can immediately transform and append these digits to form the reversed number.

**Steps:**


Initialize a result variable YYY as 000.
While X&gt;0X &gt; 0X&gt;0, extract the least significant digit (using X%10X \% 10X%10).
Compute the transformed digit using the operation dMmod‚ÄČ‚ÄČ10d^M \mod 10dMmod10.

**Special note:** If M=0M = 0M=0, every digit becomes 111, as per the problem‚Äôs definition.


Append the transformed digit to YYY by performing Y=Y√ó10+transformed_digitY = Y \times 10 + \text{transformed\_digit}Y=Y√ó10+transformed_digit.
Finally, check if Ymod‚ÄČ‚ÄČ7=0Y \mod 7 = 0Ymod7=0.
**Time Complexity:**

Since X‚Č§109X \le 10^9X‚Č§109, it has at most 10 digits. Even with MMM being as large as 100100100, at most 10√ó10010 \times 10010√ó100 iterations are needed per test case, which is efficient.

**C++ Implementation:**

`#include &lt;iostream&gt;
using namespace std;

int power_mod_10(int d, int m) {
    if (m == 0) return 1;
    int result = 1;
    for (int i = 0; i &lt; m; i++) {
        result = (result * d) % 10;
    }
    return result;
}

int main() {
    int t;
    cin &gt;&gt; t;

    while (t--) {
        long long x;
        int m;
        cin &gt;&gt; x &gt;&gt; m;

        long long y = 0;
        while (x &gt; 0) {
            int d = x % 10;
            y = y * 10 + power_mod_10(d, m);
            x /= 10;
        }

        if (y % 7 == 0)
            cout &lt;&lt; "YES\n";
        else
            cout &lt;&lt; "NO\n";
    }

    return 0;
}
