`**Idea:**

In this approach, we avoid forming the entire number YYY and instead compute Ymod‚ÄČ‚ÄČ7Y \mod 7Ymod7 directly during the transformation. This technique is beneficial when dealing with very large numbers because it circumvents potential overflow issues by maintaining only the residue modulo 777.

**Steps:**


Set a variable `modResult` to 000.
Extract digits from XXX in reverse order (using modulo operation). For each digit, compute the transformed value dMmod‚ÄČ‚ÄČ10d^M \mod 10dMmod10.
Update `modResult` using the formula:
modResult=(modResult√ó10+(transformed&nbsp;digit))mod‚ÄČ‚ÄČ7\text{modResult} = (\text{modResult} \times 10 + (\text{transformed digit})) \mod 7 modResult=(modResult√ó10+(transformed&nbsp;digit))mod7

After processing all digits, check if `modResult` is 000.
**C++ Implementation:**

`#include &lt;iostream&gt;
